  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Seeing Off Yi Pyeongsa Jang Gon
  author: Yu Sun
  language: eng
  text: |
    Changbai Mountain rises to meet the heavens,
    Its southern face is our northern gate.
    Following the ease of settlement, diverse peoples dwell,
    Their strength, by their own measure, swallows the vastness.

    These recent days the border brigands rest—
    Not through longing for the nation's grace,
    But because from ancient times this has been hallowed ground,
    Where even rats and dogs dare not speak rashly.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Changbai Mountain (長白山): The sacred mountain on the border between Goguryeo and Jurchen territories, symbolizing the northern frontier of Korea.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Border brigands: References to the Jurchen incursions that plagued Korea''s northern border during this period.'
  - key: ''
    value: The final couplet plays on Confucian dignity and territorial pride—even the lowliest creatures recognize the sanctity of heroic lands.
